contra omnium instituio] con- trary to the rules and principles of procedure observed by any of his predecessors: contained in the edicta pm‘pelua which the praetors issued on their entry into office. The rules which praetors adopted from their pre- decessors were called edictam tra- laticium, ibid ἓ 114. lt appears (ibid ἓ 119l that Verres even de- cided in some cases against his own edictum pmsseluum. To prevent this abuse a law (lex Cornelia) was passed BC 67 binding the praetor-s to administer justice in accordance with the terms of their own edicta perpetua. (Asconius' argument of the speech pro C Cor- nelio.) The principles of proce- dure and interpretation contained in the edicta constituted what was called ius praetorium and corre- sponded in effect to our Equity, correeting, supplementing, and elu- cidating the common law (ius civile).
